<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12182q"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12182q">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12182q"> 182(q)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ yellow Charles ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12182q"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Each of the three peoples threw up remarkable leaders in the final struggles under the Tudors, and no figure of those days is more notable than the MacDonnell chief, Somhairle Buidhe, &ldquo;<mark>Yellow Charles</mark>&rdquo;, Sorley Boy, as the English wrote him: and often the State Papers had occasion to write his name between 1558, when he came to lordship of the North, and 1590, when he died (singularly enough) a natural death in his own castle of Duneynie and was buried among all the Mac Donnells in the Abbey at Bonamargy near Ballycastle. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGWU" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGWU"><cite title="source">Ulster</cite></a> (1911) 25</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
